set.seed(1235)
train_id<-sample(1:nrow(df_all),size=floor(0.9*nrow(df_all)))
df_all_train<-df_all %>%slice(train_id)
df_all_test<-df_all %>%slice(-train_id)

overview of iiD

The aim of this part is to train,evaluate,tune, and compare simple to complex models via resamping.
(you may use either caret or tidymodels to handle the preprocessing,training,testing,and evaluation.)
You must train and tune the following models:
1)linear models:
a)all categorical and continuous inputs-linear additive features
b)all pairwise interactions of continuous inputs,include additive categorical features
c)the 2 models selected from iia
2)regularized regression with Elastic net
a)all pairwise interactions of continuous inputs,include additive categorical features
b)the more complex of the 2 models selected from iiA)
3)Neural network
4)random forest
5)gradient boosted tree
6)2 methods of your choice that we did not explicitly discuss in lecture decide the resamping scheme, what kind of preprocessing options you should consider, and the performance metric you will focus on.
you must identify the best model.

1)linear models

my_ctrl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 10, repeats = 3)
my_metric <- 'RMSE'

all categorical and continuous inputs-linear additive features

set.seed=(2341)
fit_lm_all_inputs <- train(log_response ~ .,
                   data = df_all_train,
                   method = "lm",
                   metric = my_metric,
                   preProcess = c("center", "scale","pca"),
                   trControl = my_ctrl)

fit_lm_all_inputs %>%readr::write_rds('fit_lm_all_inputs.rds')

all pairwise interactions of continuous inputs,include additive categorical features

                   data = df_all_train,
                   method = "lm",
                   metric = my_metric,
                   preProcess = c("center", "scale"),
                   trControl = my_ctrl)

                                      lambda = my_lambda_grid)

Based on the result of RMSE, model10,model9 and model5 are the best three models. Based on the result of Rsquared, model10,model9 and model5 are the top three best models. Based on the result of MAE, model10, model9 and mdoel 11 are the top three best models. Especially, model2 has verrrrry large value of MAE and verrrrry large value of RMSE(which doesnt show on the plot).
In conclusion, model 9(random forest model with PCA as preProcessing method) and model 10(xgbboost model with PCA as preProcessing method) are the best regression models.
